The text does not provide any information or guidance on how to submit fraudulent claims successfully. Instead, it explicitly states that if any claim made by the Insured Person is in any respect fraudulent, or if any false statement or declaration is made or used, or if any fraudulent means or devices are used by the Insured Person or anyone acting on their behalf to obtain any benefit under the policy, then:

- All benefits under the policy and the premium paid shall be forfeited.
- Any amount already paid against such fraudulent claims must be repaid by all recipients or Policyholders who made that claim, who are jointly and severally liable for repayment to the Insurer.

“Fraud” is defined as any of the following acts committed with intent to deceive the Insurer or to induce the Insurer to issue an insurance policy:

i. The suggestion, as a fact, of that which is not true and which the Insured Person does not believe to be true;

ii. The active concealment of a fact by the Insured Person having knowledge or belief of the fact;

iii. Any other act fitted to deceive;

iv. Any such act or omission as the law specially declares to be fraudulent.

The Company shall not repudiate a claim or forfeit benefits on the ground of fraud if the Insured Person or beneficiary can prove that the misstatement was true to the best of their knowledge and there was no deliberate intention to suppress the fact, or if such misstatement or suppression was within the knowledge of the Insurer.

Therefore, the text focuses exclusively on defining fraud, its consequences, and conditions under which claims will not be denied for fraud, but does not provide any information on how to submit fraudulent claims successfully.
